@course

id: book:design-everyday-things-hqmr
title: The Design of Everyday Things
author: Readlock
description: How the shape, position, and response of objects tell people what to do.
color: #059669
genres: design, psychology
relevant_for: designers, product managers, anyone

@segment
Everyday Design
ED

@package
The Door That Argued With Everyone
Free

@text
We figure out most objects without reading instructions.
A cup, a pair of scissors, or a light switch all communicate how they work before we touch them.
When that communication fails, we blame ourselves.

@text
A glass door in an office building has a flat metal plate on one side and a handle on the other.
Every morning, people on the plate side push and people on the handle side pull.
Nobody reads the sign. Nobody needs to.
The shape of the hardware tells each person what to do.
One morning, the building replaces both sides with identical handles.
Within a week, the maintenance team adds "Push" and "Pull" stickers.

@text
A pair of scissors sits on a table.
A child who has never used them picks them up correctly on the first try.
The two holes are different sizes, one for the thumb and one for the fingers.
The metal blades point away from the hand.
The shape of the object made the instructions unnecessary.
Nobody explained how scissors work to a five-year-old, the scissors explained themselves.

@text
A hotel bathroom has a single lever above the sink.
A guest pushes it left and gets hot water.
The next hotel she visits has the same lever, but reversed.
She burns her hand because she moved the lever the same way as before.
The lever looked identical in both hotels, but it meant opposite things.
Identical shapes gave opposite instructions.

@question
What do the door, the scissors, and the faucet have in common?

answer: Each object's shape told the user what to do, or failed to.
consequence: The shape communicated the action, whether the designer intended it or not.

answer: Each person needed better instructions before using the object.
consequence: The scissors worked without instructions. The problem was not missing labels.

answer: Each object was poorly designed.
consequence: The scissors were well designed. The door and faucet had shapes that misled.

correct_answers: 1
explanation: Objects communicate through their shape, and we act on what the shape suggests.
hint: Look at what guided each person's first action.

@pause
A child rarely reads instructions before picking up a new toy.

@text
The quality that makes an object communicate its use through shape is called an <c:g>affordance</c:g>.
A handle affords pulling, and a flat plate affords pushing.
The shape tells the user what the object can do before anyone explains it.
A matching affordance needs no manual, while a mismatched one gets a sticker.
The sticker is always a confession that the shape failed.

@true_false
If a product needs a label to explain how to use it, the label solves the design problem.

true: True, labels fix usability.
consequence: Labels fix the symptom, but the user still hesitates before reading the sign.

false: False, the label is a sign that the shape failed.
consequence: A label means the object's shape was not clear enough to communicate on its own.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: A well-designed object communicates through its shape. Labels patch the failure.
hint: Ask why the scissors did not need a label.

@text
An object that communicates well through shape still has another problem to solve.
The shape says what to do, but it does not always say which part controls which result.

@package
The Stove That Made Everyone Guess

@text
Have you ever stood in front of an unfamiliar stove and guessed which knob controls which burner?
Most stoves arrange four knobs in a straight line for four burners in a square.
The shape of each knob is fine, but the arrangement gives no clue about which burner it controls.

@text
You are standing at a stove with four burners arranged in a square.
The knobs are in a row along the front edge.
You turn the far-left knob and the back-right burner lights up.
You wanted the front-left burner.
There is a small diagram printed above the knobs, but you did not see it until now.
The stove works fine. The knobs simply do not match the layout of the burners.

@text
Now picture the same stove, but with the knobs rearranged.
Two knobs on the left side, two on the right, matching the square of the burners.
Left-top knob controls the left-top burner. Right-bottom knob controls the right-bottom.
You do not check the diagram this time because the layout already told you.
Every knob sits in the same position as the burner it controls.
You never guess wrong.

@question
Why did the rearranged stove not need a diagram?

answer: Because the knob positions matched the burner positions.
consequence: When the layout of controls mirrors what they control, guessing disappears.

answer: Because the second stove had better labels.
consequence: The second stove had no labels. The arrangement itself was the instruction.

answer: Because the user had already practiced on the first stove.
consequence: Practice helps, but the user got it right on the first try. The layout did the work.

correct_answers: 1
explanation: When controls mirror the layout of what they affect, labels become unnecessary.
hint: Compare the physical arrangement of knobs to the arrangement of burners.

@text
<c:g>Mapping</c:g> is what separates the two stoves.
When a control sits in the same position as the burner it affects, the mapping is natural.
When four knobs line up in a row for burners in a square, the mapping is arbitrary.
Natural mapping works without thought, while arbitrary mapping needs a diagram.
Most confusion we blame on ourselves is a mapping problem in the product.

@true_false
A product with clear labels does not need natural mapping.

true: True, labels are enough.
consequence: Labels add a step between intention and action, while natural mapping removes it.

false: False, natural mapping removes the need to read anything.
consequence: A naturally mapped control works on the first try without reading.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: Labels fix communication after the shape failed. Natural mapping prevents the failure.
hint: Ask which stove worked on the first try without reading.

@reflect
A device where you always hit the wrong button first: a car stereo or an elevator panel.
A control that felt obvious because its position matched what it controlled: a volume slider on a screen.

@text
A well-mapped control tells you what it affects before you touch it.
What it cannot tell you is whether the action worked, which is a different kind of silence.

@package
The Crosswalk Button Nobody Trusts

@text
Most crosswalk buttons in large cities are disconnected from the traffic system.
Pressing them does nothing, but almost everyone still presses.
We press because the button gives no sign that the signal heard us.

@text
A woman presses the button at a crosswalk and waits.
Nothing changes on the signal, no light, no click, and no sound.
She presses again harder, and nothing changes.
She presses a third time and holds it down.
The light changes 40 seconds later, on the same timer it always follows.
She thinks her third press worked, but the signal followed its timer the whole time.
The button had no way to tell her it received the first one.

@text
An elevator in a hospital has a different approach.
A visitor presses the call button and it lights up immediately.
A small screen shows which floor the elevator is on and which direction it is moving.
The visitor waits without pressing again.
She knows the elevator heard her because the button told her so.
The wait is the same length as the crosswalk, but the experience is completely different.

@question
Why did the elevator passenger wait calmly while the crosswalk pedestrian kept pressing?

answer: The elevator confirmed it received the request, while the crosswalk button did not.
consequence: The confirmation changed the experience, even though the wait was the same length.

answer: Elevators are faster than traffic lights.
consequence: The wait was the same length. The difference was in what the person knew during it.

answer: The pedestrian was impatient and the elevator passenger was not.
consequence: The same person would behave differently at each one. The button's response shaped the behavior.

correct_answers: 1
explanation: Confirmation after an action changes how a person experiences the wait.
hint: Ask what each person knew about whether the system heard them.

@pause
A microwave that beeps when it starts gives the cook permission to walk away.

@text
The missing piece in the crosswalk and the present piece in the elevator is <c:g>feedback</c:g>.
<c:g>Feedback</c:g> is any signal that tells a person their action was received and what happened next.
A light that turns on, a click, or a change on a screen.
Without it, people repeat the action, press harder, or give up.
With it, they trust the system and wait.

@true_false
If a product works correctly, it does not need to tell the user what just happened.

true: True, correct function is enough.
consequence: A working product that stays silent looks identical to a broken one.

false: False, silence after an action feels the same as failure.
consequence: Without a signal, the user cannot tell if the product worked.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: A product that works but stays silent is indistinguishable from one that failed.
hint: Ask how the user knows the difference between working and broken.

@reflect
A button you pressed twice because nothing confirmed the first press: a crosswalk or a remote.
A device that made waiting easy by showing what was happening: a download progress bar.

@text
Every object in this course communicated something, whether through shape, position, or response.
The question none of them can answer is what happens when we stop noticing.
